'''LiquiGlide''' is a platform technology which creates slippery, [[liquid-impregnated surface]]s that was developed at the Varanasi Research Group at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] by Prof. Kripa Varanasi and his team of students and post doctorals Dave Smith, Rajeev Dhiman, Adam Paxson, Brian Solomon, and Chris Love.<ref name="fcomp">{{cite news|url=http://www.fastcoexist.com/1679878/mits-freaky-non-stick-coating-keeps-ketchup-flowing|title=MIT’s freaky non-stick coating keeps ketchup flowing|last=Carr|first=Austin|date=May 22, 2012|accessdate=May 26, 2012|work=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/256085/mits_liquiglide_may_end_ketchup_bottle_frustrations_for_all_eternity.html|title=MIT's LiquiGlide may end ketchup bottle frustrations for all eternity|last=Filice|first=Albert|date=May 23, 2012|accessdate=May 26, 2012|work=[[PCWorld (magazine)|PCWorld]]}}</ref> Possible applications include improving the [[Flow measurement|flow rate]] of [[condiment]] bottles to avoid [[food waste]], and preventing clogs in gas and oil tubes.<ref name="fcomp" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-05-24/news/ct-talk-liquiglide-ketchup-bottles-0525-20120524_1_ketchup-bottles-condiment|title=Non-stick ketchup bottles? Yes, says MIT team|last=Manker|first=Rob|date=May 24, 2012|accessdate=May 26, 2012|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> The inventors released videos of LiquiGlide being used in [[ketchup]], [[mayonnaise]], [[Fruit preserves|jelly]], and [[mustard (condiment)|mustard]] bottles made of both [[plastic]] and [[glass]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liquiglide.com/applications/|title=LiquiGlide demo videos|publisher=Varanasi Research Group|date=May 23, 2012|accessdate=May 26, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130916100032/http://www.liquiglide.com/applications/|archivedate=September 16, 2013|df=}}</ref> The project came in second place in the Business Plan Contest and won the Audience Choice Award at the 2012 [[MIT $100K Entrepreneurship Competition]].<ref name="fcomp" />
In March 2015, LiquiGlide signed a deal with [[Elmer's Products]], the first company to use the technology.<ref>Victoria Woollaston, [http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-3009107/End-whacking-ketchup-bottle-Scientists-sign-deal-bring-revolutionary-non-stick-coating-supermarket-shelves.html The end of whacking the ketchup bottle is nigh! Scientists sign first deal to bring revolutionary non-stick coating to supermarket shelves], March 24, 2015</ref>
