{{weather-stub}}

The '''viriome''' of a [[habitat]] or environment is the total [[virus]] content within it.<ref name="HugenholtzTyson2008">{{cite journal|last1=Hugenholtz|first1=Philip|last2=Tyson|first2=Gene W.|title=Microbiology: Metagenomics|journal=Nature|volume=455|issue=7212|year=2008|pages=481–483|issn=0028-0836|doi=10.1038/455481a}}</ref> A viriome may relate to the viruses that inhabit a [[multicellular organism]] as well as the [[phages]] that are residing inside [[bacteria]] and [[archaea]].
This term exists in contrast to the [[virome]], which more commonly refers to the collection of [[nucleic acids]] contained by viruses in a [[microbiome]].
==See also== * [[Human virome]] *[[Non-cellular life]] *[[Microbiology]] *[[Metagenomics]]
